<gtr:id>265E1C86-E5A9-4A92-8DC1-AF7684A95CA2</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Bregje</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Christina</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>de Kok</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE004091%2F1"><gtr:id>687EFF7A-BED3-4813-835F-A65A4DBC8AFB</gtr:id><gtr:title>Childbearing in Malawi: Constructions of pregnancy loss and maternal mortality</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E004091/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>In developing countries, infertility has serious psychological and social consequences, usually attributed to norms mandating parenthood. This doctoral research investigates social constructions of infertility, its causes, solutions and consequences in Malawi. Interviews were conducted with people with a fertility problem, their significant others and traditional and biomedical health practitioners. They were analysed using discourse analysis (Potter &amp;amp; Wetherell, 1987), informed by conversation analysis (Sacks, 1992); a novel approach in infertility studies. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>It examines the interpersonal functions of statements in interaction, such as blaming or justifying. This analytic approach led to new insights into how interpersonal, normative and moral issues are managed in constructions of infertility. These issues revolve around the management of ;&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>Accountability (eg for seeking solutions, not curing infertility);&lt;br />&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Blame (eg avoiding blaming others for troubled relationships); and&lt;br />&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Problematic identities (eg incompetent healer).&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>The main aims of this postdoctoral fellowship include dissemination of the PhD findings and development of a research proposal to examine other forms of loss in childbearing in Malawi, including abortions, miscarriage and stillbirth and loss of the mother (ie maternal mortality). The outputs of this project will be beneficial for the development of reproductive health policy, health promotion and health service design.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-07-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-12-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>119279</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E004091/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Psychology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Anthropology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-BA5E-562216587E68</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Sociology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352